<img width="100px" class="rounded float-start pe-4" src="../img/thought.jpg">

As a newbie to TypeScript, I have found it to be an intriguing and relatively straightforward programming language. At first, I thought I would have a hard time understanding another program but I've been pleasantly surprised, especially when comparing it to Java, a language I am more familiar with.  

My first impression of TypeScript, is that it introduces static typing to the dynamic world of JavaScript. This addition of types has been a game-changer for me. Coming from a background in Java, where static typing is the norm, TypeScript’s type system felt like a natural extension. The ability to catch errors at compile-time rather than at runtime has significantly improved my development experience. The language’s syntax is clean and intuitive, making it easy to pick up even for someone new to it.

In conclusion, my foray into TypeScript has been a rewarding experience. The language’s blend of static typing, modern features, and seamless JavaScript integration makes it an excellent choice for web development. While it differs from Java in several ways, TypeScript offers a unique set of advantages that make it a valuable addition to any developer’s toolkit. As I continue to explore and learn more about TypeScript, I am excited about the possibilities it holds for building robust and scalable applications.
